      "title": "Small mammals of wheat fields and fallow wheat fields in north-central Kansas",
      "abstract": "Small mammals were trapped monthly in wheat fields (Triticum aestivum1), fallow wheat fields, and grazed breaks prairie sites in Lincoln and Russell counties, Kansas from February 1983 to February 1984. The deer mouse (Peromnyscus maniculatus) was the most common species in each of the three habitats (94% of 559 individuals captured in wheat fields; 83% of 760 in fallow wheat fields; 86% of 528 in breaks prairie). Fallow field was the preferred habitat for deer mice, western harvest mice (Reithrodontomys inegalotis), cotton rats (Sigmnodon hispidus), and house mice (Mus musculus); breaks prairie for grasshopper mice (Onychomnys leucogaster) and hispid pocket mice (Chaetodipus hispidus); and wheat and fallow wheat fields for prairie voles (Alicrotus ochrogaster). Data from this and other studies in north-central Kansas suggest that conversion of native prairie to wheat production has shifted the abundance and composition of the assemblage of native prairie rodents. Changes associated with this shift included both greater abundance and greater numerical domination of the assemblage by deer mice, little effect on grasshopper mice, but a reduction in abundance and proportional contribution to the assemblage by western and plains harvest mice, pocket mice, prairie voles, and ground squirrels. One of the changes brought by human settlement was the conversion of forests and grasslands to crop fields, a change that undoubtedly had an impact on native wildlife species including small mammals (Fleharty and Navo, 1983; Houtcooper, 1978a; Navo and Fleharty, 1983; Whittaker, 1967). In north-central Kansas, approximately one-half of the native mixed-grass prairie was converted to cropland following settlement (based on Lincoln and Russell counties; Barker and Hamilton, 1985; Jantz et al., 1982). With increased concerns about the impacts of human activities on wildlife, it is necessary for biologists and conservationists to understand habitat distribution and requirements of native animals, including their use of agricultural lands. Only limited natural history and ecological data on the effects of various land practices are available for small mammals in Kansas. Such This content downloaded from 157.55.39.132 on Thu, 15 Sep 2016 05:48:50 UTC All use subject to http://about.jstor.org/terms VOLUME 93, NUMBERS 1-2 29 information is valuable for developing habitat management practices and for understanding how different land uses affect small mammals. Objectives, herein, are to assess and describe the use of wheat fields (Triticum aestivum) and fallow wheat fields by small mammals in north-central Kansas and to examine how the composition of the prairie rodent assemblage differs between native prairie and cropland used for wheat production. STUDY AREA AND METHODS Small mammals were censused using 150 traplines set in wheat fields, fallow wheat fields, and limestone breaks prairie in T 11S, R 11W; T1 iS, R12W; T12S, Ri 1W; and T12S, R12W in Russell County and TI IS, R10W in Lincoln County, Kansas. Each trapline consisted of 20 stations with a 15 m spacing between stations. Three Museum Special snap traps baited with peanut butter were placed at each station. Traps were set and checked for three consecutive nights each month from February 1983 to February 1984, with the full moon period of each month avoided. In March 1983, a heavy snow prevented the third night of trapping on two lines set in wheat fields, one in fallow field, and two in breaks prairie. Small mammals were censused with 50 traplines set in wheat fields (number of traplines set per month: 0, 4, 4, 4, 4, 4, 8, 4, 4, 4, 2, 4, 4); 49 traplines in fallow wheat fields (6, 5, 5, 3, 4, 2, 2, 4, 4, 4, 2, 4, 4); and 51 in grazed limestone breaks sites (4, 4, 4, 4, 4, 5, 4, 4, 4, 4, 2, 4, 4). Total trap nights were 8880 in wheat fields, 8760 in fallow fields, and 9060 in breaks prairie. Wheat fields consisted of growing wheat during March-May; standing wheat nearly ready to be harvested during June; standing wheat stubble for two lines and recently disked for two lines during July; standing wheat stubble for four lines and recently disked for four lines during August; wheat fields cultivated two or more times in preparation for fall planting during September-October; and growing wheat, planted in October, during NovemberFebruary. Fallow wheat fields in February-August were fields from which wheat had been harvested in late June to early July 1982 and September-February were fields from which wheat had been harvested in late June to early July 1983. During these censuses, sites with standing stubble were 3 of 6 lines in February 1983 and 2 of 5, 2 of 5, 3 of 3, 4 of 4, 0 of 2, 0 of 2, 4 of 4, 4 of 4, 4 of 4, 2 of 2, 2 of 4, and 3 of 4 in succeeding months. The limestone breaks sites were in mixed-grass prairie dominated by a bluestem-grama (Andropogon-Bouteloua) association (Barker and Hamilton, 1985; Kiichler, 1974). All prairie sites were grazed by cattle during the growing season and had been during most of the years since settlement. In breaks sites, traplines followed the curved outcropping of the limestone and, therefore, were not set as straight census lines as in the other two habitat"
    }
